The words were strained, and her daughter could see the severe pain in her mother's eyes. "Okay Mom, guide me on how to help you," she replied. With her mother’s direction, she relied on her strength training to lift her into the car, laying her gently in the back, and drove to the hospital.

The hospital greeted her with the familiar smells of antiseptic and anxiety, but her focus remained solely on her mother’s wellbeing. Swiftly, she carried her into the building, urgently seeking medical assistance. A cluster of concerned staff gathered, one of them quickly bringing a gurney to lay her mother upon. They whisked her away for immediate care, leaving the daughter in a state of anxious waiting.

Her mother had taken a tumble from a step stool while attempting to reach a vase on the top shelf of their highest cabinet.

This research aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a decreased risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke mortality. The aMed diet is an adapted form of the traditional Med diet, distinguished by increased consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but incorporating fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (in preference to saturated fats), and fish, while reducing the intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permissible.

Previous prospective studies have shown an inverse relationship between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of overall and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. Additionally, an intervention trial indicated that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and enhancing the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Earlier research did not specifically concentrate on stroke or stroke mortality.

In this epidemiological study, researchers monitored 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, with no prior history of CVD or diabetes, who were participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. The study spanned from 1984 to 2004, during which the authors calculated an aMed diet score on six occasions using self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs”) intended to evaluate nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of the nurses remained involved throughout the 20-year duration. The FFQs underwent validation checks. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through examination of medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, incidents were deemed “probable” and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions falling into this category. Factors such as body mass index, smoking status, aspirin usage, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To minimize random variation for an individual and provide a better representation of long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were computed (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments for confounding factors (elements that might skew results) were made by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was employed to evaluate the relationship between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, with separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke cases.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, correlated with a reduced risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. Over the 20-year follow-up, there were 2391 new cases of CHD, 1763 new cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease-related deaths (combining fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the highest aMed quintile exhibited a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign reads: Hitler is alive in Burma.

Standing solitary on a street corner, Ellen Page, the renowned actress from *Juno*, holds a piece of cardboard above her head with the alarming message inscribed in Sharpie. Burma, also called Myanmar, is a nation in Southeast Asia governed by a repressive military junta that seized control via a coup d’état in 1962. In 2007, the country witnessed the first public demonstrations in a decade. These protests, led predominantly by Burmese monks, became known as "The Saffron Revolution," named after the hue of the monks' robes. Initially, the Burmese government reluctantly permitted the monks to assemble peacefully, but as the protests gained public interest, the situation quickly deteriorated into violent clashes between the military junta and the monks. The military began raiding monasteries nationwide, and foreign journalists were detained, with a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, fatally shot during a protest on September 27, 2007. Although the official death toll is recorded as 13, Colonel Hla Win, an army defector, claimed, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

Such events are not new. While these are recent instances of global atrocities, the ambition of governments to suppress dissent and exert absolute control over their citizens has persisted throughout history. In ancient Rome, emperors claimed divine selection for absolute authority over societal facets. Japanese emperors are deemed divine, destined to lead their people to prosperity through the creation of inventions like Motorola cell phones and practices like hara-kiri. Meanwhile, our then-president, George W. Bush, reportedly held weekly calls with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subgroup of the Republic Party.

Noteworthy examples of such actions include the Tiananmen Square protests on June 4, 1989, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered against governmental authoritarianism. The death toll estimates from this event vary significantly, with official Chinese reports citing 200-300 fatalities, while the Chinese Red Cross reported 2,000-3,000 deaths. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militias, supported by the Rwandan government, systematically exterminated Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of ethnicity. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’ stands as an extreme instance, where countless individuals of Jewish descent were persecuted and executed over several years across numerous nations.

Duke Ellington's enduring influence in jazz largely stems from his long career and his exceptional talent in shaping his orchestra's sound. While his piano presence is often understated in the selections for this assignment, Ellington's genius as a composer shines through in his ability to create intricate and complex compositions that highlight the unique talents of his band members. He laid the groundwork for soloists to freely improvise, while also crafting meticulously orchestrated pieces that showcased the distinct styles of his musicians, effectively bringing out musical themes. This approach allowed him to emphasize the orchestra's overall tone, resulting in cohesive and original sounds tailored to each piece. Ellington's profound understanding of individual players' sounds and how they harmonized within an evolving ensemble led to some of the most groundbreaking and brilliant works in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary, in its discussion of Ellington's sound and innovation, cites "Creole Love Call" as an example of his use of voice as a "jazz instrument" throughout his career. This piece illustrates Ellington's skill in adding vocal texture and color without relying on lyrics, and it demonstrates his knack for complementing the style of his soloists, a hallmark of his career. The slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece consists of six choruses:

Chorus 1: Features a call-and-response between voice and reeds, starting with a smooth, melodic tone that shifts to a rougher sound by the end.  
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that expands on the melody and highlights several extended blue notes.  
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, accompanied by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.  
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with a call-and-response between the brass and reed sections.  
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus with reeds leading the call-and-response in a high register, supported by syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections.  
Chorus 6: Returns to the first chorus structure, with call-and-response between voice and reeds, where the voice employs the "growl" technique, acting as an instrument.  
Tag: Concludes with a brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add tonal color in this piece is a stylistic trait seen throughout his work. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington merges his mastery of tight orchestration with his keen sense for tonal color. A call-and-response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses the vocal qualities of Miley's playing and the instrumental characteristics of Cox's voice to create a rich, complementary sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" further develops these ideas, as Ellington effectively employs Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a key figure in Ellington's orchestra, to introduce the melody on muted trombone.

What factors influence the way organisms evolve? Are there limitations or constraints shaping the direction of evolutionary changes? Back in 1917, D’Arcy Thompson remarked that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," and this observation holds true today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to study general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis, considering both their development and evolutionary history (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research investigates how mathematical modeling of developmental and evolutionary changes in the genus Prunum, alongside experimental studies, can help unveil the mechanisms driving the direction and scale of evolutionary-developmental transformations. We utilized X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters, which were then used to model both hypothetical and actual skeletal forms. These parameters were fed into the CerioShell software (Stone, 1995). By modeling hypothetical shell forms, we aimed to interpret the limits of potential morphological changes in Prunum. The findings are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to gain a better understanding of macroevolutionary processes in this group.

A shell can be conceptualized as a structure resembling a tube that spirals through 360 degrees over time. These spirals or turns of a coiled shell are known as whorls, which encircle an imaginary central axis. This axis extends through the shell's central column, termed the columella. The growth rate of the whorls can differ, with each whorl separated by a continuous line called a suture. Typically, the largest whorl is the final one, known as the body whorl. The spire includes all whorls except the last one, while the apex is the tip of the spire and the base is at the opposite end. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be observed from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is the apertural view, where the aperture faces the viewer with the apex pointing upwards.)

To count the whorls, start by viewing the shell from the apical perspective and identify where the first suture begins. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a sequence of apertures moving through time and space as the animal builds its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced using coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture and the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This path can be represented both graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical model is established, it becomes possible to adjust parameters and alter the mollusk’s shell formation process.

Over the past decade, Indonesia has witnessed little change in its neonatal and infant mortality rates. While the nation appears to be on track with several Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, the expected progress in child and maternal health remains significantly lacking to meet the 2015 targets. The underlying causes of these deficiencies are explored below, suggesting a focus on reinforcing the healthcare system rather than just implementing program-specific interventions.

Indonesia has seen some advancement in the presence of skilled health professionals at births, with 72% of deliveries now attended by such personnel. However, this statistic includes traditional workers like midwives, who are not equipped to handle medical complications during childbirth, contributing to the high maternal mortality rate due to hemorrhage. Hence, the progress in this area is somewhat deceptive, indicating that substantial efforts are still necessary. Moreover, there has been a reduction in the number of children under five with diarrhea being treated by health professionals. Although data on postnatal care remains sparse, it's evident that this area requires attention due to low nationwide rates.

Cesarean-section rates are lower than anticipated, hovering around 4%. This figure highlights another significant concern. In urban regions, the c-section rate is 7%, whereas in rural areas, it is a mere 2%, revealing disparities in healthcare access. Health services are evidently more accessible in urban areas. Another access issue pertains to vertical equity, with a 27% disparity in service use between the poorest and wealthiest segments. This indicates that poorer individuals face greater obstacles in accessing healthcare, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

When considering strategies to enhance neonatal and maternal care indicators, a fundamental question arises: should Indonesia focus on service-specific approaches or bolster the overall health system, irrespective of pre and post-natal care? Program-specific strategies are appealing since they offer precise, manageable goals and often yield quicker results. However, there are significant drawbacks. Prioritizing one health sector can divert funds from others and concentrate human resources in that area, as seen with international funding for HIV/AIDS impacting the family planning sector. Additionally, operating multiple parallel programs can lead to service duplication and uncoordinated efforts, increasing the administrative burden for supplies and funding.

Over the past century, the classification of popular music has expanded to encompass a vast array of genres, making it challenging to catalog them comprehensively. Adding to this complexity, nearly every genre—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—has given rise to numerous sub-genres and even sub-sub-genres. Notably, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has emerged as one of the most varied and expressive genres within popular music over the last four decades. Its expressiveness is evident in its wide emotional range, often gravitating towards darker themes. Its diversity became apparent early on, as enthusiasts recognized its inherent flexibility and began crafting their own sub-genres, which in turn spawned further sub-sub-genres, a trend that continues to this day.

Currently, the heavy metal scene is so fragmented with specialized niches that defining heavy metal itself has become a challenge. It has absorbed numerous elements from other genres, yet, like all music forms, it originated from a specific point. To truly grasp the metal music prevalent today, one must first comprehend what constitutes the metal movement and why it transcends being merely a genre.

In many respects, metal is a movement characterized by its affinity for darkness. It can be described as music that embodies excess—more bass, more volume, more intensity, more theatrical flair. There is less primitivism, and more technical skill; musicians in metal bands are often highly proficient, and this expertise is reflected in their music. Moreover, metal is—perhaps unsurprisingly—deeply intertwined with drug culture. The psychedelic drug wave of the mid-1970s led to increasingly experimental and otherworldly music productions, with artists using drugs as a catalyst for their creativity. Metal's dark, visceral qualities were a novel addition to the music scene, contrasting sharply with the lighter emotional tones of much popular music. Subsequent generations of metal bands have drawn inspiration from these dark, visceral elements, reminiscent of the Romantic Era’s influence. Lyrics like those from Helter Skelter illustrate the movement's signature darkness.

These lyrics from Helter Skelter reveal the darker aspects of the Beatles, reflecting a tumultuous, perhaps drug-influenced experience. This track is often regarded as one of the earliest Heavy Metal songs, crafted in response to a similarly heavy and dark Rolling Stones track. The Beatles aimed to demonstrate their ability to match the Stones' intensity, which is why the song was included on The White Album.

Long before the Surrealist painters began their exploration of dreamlike imagery, Henri Rousseau was crafting his own visions, both in his art and ambitions. His 1910 painting, The Dream, not only portrays a woman entranced by the wonders of a dreamt landscape but also symbolizes Rousseau’s personal aspirations as an artist. From the onset of his career, Rousseau longed for recognition and admiration from fellow artists and the art community. However, achieving this dream was fraught with internal conflict. The Dream encapsulates Rousseau's lifelong struggle—whether to conform to prevailing artistic styles to gain acceptance in the critical art world he cherished or to remain true to his unique creative voice and forge his own path.

To fully appreciate The Dream through this lens, one must understand Rousseau’s background. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France, Rousseau was the son of a tinsmith and hardware merchant who enjoyed moderate prosperity (Shattuck 47). He received no formal art education and worked for the French municipal toll service, often mistakenly referred to as a customs inspector, until he was forty (Shattuck 46). The loss of his first wife, Clémence, and eight of their children, leaving only a daughter named Julia, plunged Rousseau into deep sorrow (Shattuck 49). Seeking solace, he turned to painting as a means of renewal and comfort. Unlike his contemporaries who often romanticized rural life, Rousseau’s work reflected the aspirations and experiences of the average person of his social standing.

Rousseau’s yearning for acceptance in the art world is understandable when considered in context. Untrained and starting his art career later in life, he competed alongside other acclaimed modern artists. Only after years of effort did Rousseau start gaining recognition, around the time Matisse was establishing his reputation. In Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon notes the contrast between the two; while Matisse feared falling into artistic clichés, Rousseau sought to create works conventional enough to earn him a place in the Artiste Français (Gordon 92).

Throughout history, numerous intellectuals have suggested a close relationship between ethics and aesthetics, and between truth and beauty. I am convinced that there is a fundamental reason behind this connection. As John Keats eloquently puts it in “Ode on a Grecian Urn,” “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of our knowledge comes from education or experience, yet our appreciation of ethics and aesthetics, as Keats hints, seems to arise without formal instruction. Both areas attempt to describe rather than dictate. Our exploration of morality and beauty largely aims to explain what makes a piece of art or literature beautiful, or an action moral, rather than establishing rules for creating good art or ethical behavior.

Critiquing art or morality often falls short of capturing the essence of what is good or beautiful. A discussion about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might involve concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural significance, but these don't fully explain why it is considered great art. When someone speaks about a favorite artwork or piece of literature, they often say, “There's just something about it,” before offering a more detailed analysis. I believe that art and morals cannot be entirely distilled into a list of qualities. As Flannery O'Connor remarks, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” Even with a thorough description of a literary work, something transcendent remains. I see the same quality in ethics. As Wittgenstein points out, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental.” I propose that this indefinable quality, this je ne sais quoi, is the most compelling aspect of art and morality, and it is this transcendental nature that links ethics and aesthetics.

I believe that the close relationship between morality and art stems from their profound impact on us at a noumenal level, to borrow a term from Kant. We experience them deeply, yet cannot fully explain them. This connection is particularly strong in the realm of literature. As McKean states, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Modern Germany is recognized as a formidable and cohesive nation with a diverse cultural identity stretching from the Alpine region of Munich to the Baltic city of Kiel. This cultural essence is discernible from Cologne on the Rhine River, traversing central Germany to Dresden on the Elbe. Given its distinctive heritage, it is no surprise that contemporary Germany emerged from a mix of various origins and tribes.

The ancestral roots of the German people lie in Germania, though the name's origins are debated among experts. According to Tacitus, the name came from the Tungrians, a Germanic tribe, previously known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and engaged the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar was the first to use "Germanus" in his writings on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and encountered Germanic tribes who frequently crossed the Rhine with dubious intentions. He adopted this term from the Gauls to differentiate between those he had vanquished (the Gauls) and those he had not. While the origin remains uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish tongue. In his initial account of these wars, Caesar observes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others suggest the name derives from the weapon they wielded, a spear known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim, meaning “to shout,” implying that the Germans were boisterous. (Names of Germany)

The early Roman chronicler Tacitus, in his AD 98 work “De Origine et situ Germanorum,” which explored the Germans' origins, noted, “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98)

And who would abandon Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not initially. They ventured into Germania for resources and occasionally embarked on land campaigns but typically returned to their vast empire. As the Germanic tribes emerged in the first century, they resided on the fringes of the Roman Empire, trading goods and offering their services as soldiers in the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play "Twelfth Night" explores the notion that while disguises can effectively sustain prolonged deception, ultimately, one must abandon these facades to avoid losing their true identity. However, ceasing such deception poses a significant challenge, as it may lead to feelings of isolation. Consequently, individuals are faced with the choice between safeguarding their own identity or maintaining relationships with those around them. Some may react indifferently to the revelation of deception, yet others may feel deeply offended by the deceit.

The theme of deception related to gender role reversal is particularly complex, as it raises several questions, most notably, the reason behind the disguise. Why would someone abandon their identity to assume the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it is clearly a measure of self-preservation: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). Upon arriving in an unfamiliar land, Viola feels compelled to masquerade as a man for protection against potential threats. Her strategy is successful, but it also isolates her from other women, depriving her of crucial support. To complicate matters further, her disguise is so convincing that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and, consequently, falls in love with her: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Additionally, she must navigate her repressed romantic feelings for Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261).

Although this might be seen as a progressive perspective, contemporary readers may view "Twelfth Night" as showcasing how deception can reveal hidden emotions, particularly in Olivia and Orsino's cases. Certain scenes suggest that these characters might possess unacknowledged desires that Viola/Cesario's presence compels them to confront. For instance, is Olivia drawn to Cesario because she believes Cesario is male, or does she secretly have feelings for women? It seems improbable, as Shakespeare's portrayal of Olivia appears to mock those of his era who judge others based solely on appearances. This is evident in Olivia's swift shift of affection from Cesario to Sebastian, eventually regarding Cesario/Viola as a sibling rather than a romantic partner: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

German colonial rule is often remembered for its harshness, particularly concerning the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama peoples in what was then German South West Africa. However, it is important to recognize that no colonial empire can be fully described with such a broad statement. The German colonial empire displayed a wide range of policies and governing styles, differing as much as its geographic spread. Educational offerings across the colonies were similarly varied. When the British assumed control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a substantial number of well-educated and literate Africans. German educational initiatives in Kamerun and other territories were also lauded by writers of the period.

In contrast, the situation in South West Africa (modern-day Namibia) was notably different. Unlike East Africa, where the government actively established state schools and contributed significantly to the education of the local population, in South West Africa, the responsibility for native education was largely handed over to missionary societies with minimal government assistance. The government did, however, allocate considerable resources to the education of Europeans within the colony, developing a system of state schools and providing greater support and regulation for missionary schools. These educational policies left a lasting impact on South West Africa, even beyond the period of German rule. While other German colonies saw a significant number of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." A variety of social, political, and economic factors contributed to the different experiences in South West Africa. This paper aims to broaden the discussion by identifying these factors and highlighting recent research on the perceptions of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There exists an extensive body of literature focused specifically on education within the German colonial empire. Most of these texts are in German and were composed in the early 20th century, during or shortly after German colonial rule. The primary goal of these early works was to detail the characteristics of educational systems within these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse by offering comparative studies of education across various German colonies and providing more in-depth analyses of specific educational aspects. These studies highlighted significant disparities in the educational systems of different colonies. Notably, Cohen's study on education in South West Africa and East Africa directly addresses the topic of this paper. Cohen contrasts the educational systems of the two colonies and explores the factors contributing to their differences. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa accounts for many of the distinctive features of its educational system.

Relative to Germany's other colonial holdings, South West Africa enjoyed a somewhat temperate climate, although much of the area is characterized by arid desert. The European population in South West Africa mirrored the relatively favorable living conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, compared to only 5,336 in East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population.

The United States of America and Mexico once experienced a prolonged and challenging period of rivalry that lasted for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). This rivalry reached its peak during the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, when the United States launched an attack on Mexico, resulting in a victory that allowed it to annex Texas and the American Southwest. Several other conflicts occurred between these two nations, finally subsiding just before the outbreak of the First World War. The root of the rivalry lay in significant disagreements over religion, culture, and tradition, as well as a substantial clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

This situation is reminiscent of numerous other countries that have long-standing rivalries with their neighbors. Nations that share borders often encounter conflicting interests, which can give rise to adversarial positions. The case of the United States and Mexico mirrors many enduring rivalries between neighboring countries. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both Mexico and Cuba are geographically close to the United States and have maintained rivalrous relationships with it, in contrast to other Latin American countries that have generally enjoyed amicable relations with the United States.

Religious differences significantly contributed to the divide between the United States and Mexico, a challenge that has troubled many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) argues that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). Similar to the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which combined ideological struggle with competition over perceived vital interests, the conflict between the United States and Mexico was rooted in religious disparities rather than political structures. This mutual distrust stemmed from the historical animosity between the English and Spanish, which the United States and Mexico inherited from their colonial predecessors, complicating efforts to establish friendly diplomatic relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) identify 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during their 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes involved territorial issues, such as border raids from Mexican territory and other frontier challenges. Raids by bandits and outlaws on American border towns were a persistent problem until both the United States and Mexico deployed military forces to secure their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97). Schmitt (1974) notes that the rivalry began to diminish as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109) and ultimately concluded as American ambitions shifted "from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico" (p.110) in the latter part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years back, my life took an unexpected turn when I was suddenly disabled by a condition I had never heard of before.

At that time, I was working as a nurse. I had selected this career driven by a deep-seated need for the stability and security that I lacked during my childhood. "You'll always have a job; people will always need medical care," was a constant refrain throughout my teen years and beyond. So, even though my aspirations leaned towards becoming a scientist or a journalist—or perhaps both—I opted for a career in nursing.

However, at 46, I found myself single, without any savings, and unable to work. I remain disabled to this day, and after 15 years of relying on Social Security Disability benefits, I find myself with virtually nothing to claim as my own. I manage to get by, but each day is a battle that challenges my sense of security, safety, and self-worth. Nothing in my life feels stable anymore, but there is one truth I hold onto: without the support of my family and a few close friends, I would not have survived these years, regardless of my personal strength. When true calamity hits, you certainly don't feel very strong.

The reality is that life will always throw unexpected challenges our way, both big and small. No level of preparation can guarantee security, as some obstacles are simply too overwhelming to face alone.

I firmly believe that in the U.S., we need to move away from relying solely on the government, which is showing signs of decay and instability. Instead, I would prefer to see Americans fostering trust and cooperation—supporting one another and being willing to seek support—rather than each person independently preparing for doomsday scenarios.

While the U.S. Conservatives praise "rugged individualism" as a cornerstone of our nation's history, the truth is that our ancestors persevered through tough times not because of individualism but through compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. Those who traveled in wagon trains across the Rockies didn't succeed by going it alone.

So, yes, be prepared. I am. I've assembled a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and materials to seal windows in case of a biological threat. I have multiple flashlights, a variety of batteries, an abundance of candles, waterproof matches, and canned food. If you have the land and resources to maintain a small farm and preserve your own food, go for it. It's a wise choice, as is investing in a wood stove, provided you don't live in an apartment.

But as you prepare, take the time to get to know your neighbors.

In the distant past, around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later become known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he chose to leave behind worldly life and achieved enlightenment. His teachings became the foundation of Buddhism, with the most traditional branch being Theravada Buddhism. This religion has a history spanning approximately 2,500 years and has evolved significantly since Buddha's time. This evolution is evident in various places, such as Sri Lanka, a predominantly Theravada Buddhist country, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is celebrated. Both monks and laypeople take part in this event, which holds religious meaning despite not being part of Buddha's original teachings. These variations range from ceremonial practices to the fundamental beliefs of the religion. Over time, the Theravada Buddhist community, both monastic and lay, has had to adapt its doctrines due to various influences, both from within and outside the community, as well as both supportive and challenging forces.

Several key terms will be frequently utilized in this discussion. The idea of internal versus external forces is one of these. Internal forces are those that originate from members of the Buddhist community, regardless of their monastic status. External forces refer to influences from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is one that harms or seeks to harm the Buddhist community, stemming from a negative view of Buddhism. Conversely, a benign force does not aim to either harm or assist the Buddhist community, although it might inadvertently do so. These terms will be referenced multiple times throughout the discussion.

To begin, it is crucial to explore the fundamental aspects of the religion—the essential doctrines of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially made up of the Tripitaka, or "three baskets," of Buddhist scriptures. The Sutta Pitaka comprises all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the rules of discipline, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka deals with the metaphysical elements of Buddhism. These metaphysical ideas include concepts like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (the inherent suffering in life), and Anicca (impermanence of all things). By understanding these concepts, one can end Sansara, the continuous cycle of death and rebirth. With the cessation of Sansara comes the end of lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion), leading to enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for living. Laypeople follow five precepts: refraining from killing, lying, stealing, sexual misconduct, and taking intoxicants. Monks adhere to many more rules of discipline. The most essential doctrinal aspect in Buddhism is the four noble truths: first, the truth of Dukkha, acknowledging that life involves suffering; second, that attachment leads to suffering; and third, that suffering can be overcome.
